<item>
            <title>[DERBY-772] Handle pushing IN predicates into UNIONs. This would allow use of index if present improving performance.</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DERBY-772</link>
                <project id="10594" key="DERBY">Derby</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;While fix for &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DERBY-649&quot; title=&quot;Useful indexes not used in UNION ALL&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;DERBY-649&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;DERBY-649&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; allows pushing binary predicates into SELECT statements that are underneath a UNOIN, it would also be good to allow IN operations to be pushed. Derby can rewrite IN operations in a way to allow use of index, if present.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Derby currently rewrites: REF IN (1, 2, 3) to REF &amp;gt;=1 and REF &amp;lt;=3 and hence would allow use of index on REF, if present. Pushing this predicate into Union would allow use of index on REF for queries like:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Select * from &lt;br/&gt;
     (SELECT REF, NAME from T1 UNION ALL SELECT REF, NAME from t2)&lt;br/&gt;
where REF IN (1,2,3)&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>generic</environment>
